P10.fix_sketch:
Rust-only fix (Python is the reference and already correct; byte-parity means Rust must move to Python's behavior). In crates/clankerprof-core/src/rules.rs, replace the lines()-then-first_csv_field pipeline with a quote-aware record scanner that implements csv.reader's default dialect over the whole payload, then take field 0 of each record:

fn core_classes_from_csv(payload: &str) -> BTreeSet<String> {
    let mut values = BTreeSet::new();
    let mut chars = payload.chars().peekable();
    while chars.peek().is_some() {
        let mut first_field = String::new();
        let mut in_quotes = false;
        let mut past_first = false;   // seen the first comma of this record
        let mut any = false;          // record is non-empty (csv.reader skips blank lines as [])
        while let Some(ch) = chars.next() {
            if in_quotes {
                any = true;
                if ch == '"' {
                    if chars.peek() == Some(&'"') { if !past_first { first_field.push('"'); } chars.next(); }
                    else { in_quotes = false; }
                } else if !past_first { first_field.push(ch); }   // embedded newlines included
                continue;
            }
            match ch {
                '"' => { in_quotes = true; any = true; }          // csv.reader non-strict: quotes re-open mid-field
                ',' => { past_first = true; any = true; }
                '\r' => { if chars.peek() == Some(&'\n') { chars.next(); } break; }
                '\n' => break,
                other => { any = true; if !past_first { first_field.push(other); } }
            }
        }
        if any {
            let value = first_field.trim().to_string();
            if !value.is_empty() && !value.starts_with('#') { values.insert(value); }
        }
    }
    values
}

Delete first_csv_field (or keep it only if reused elsewhere — it is not). Note this also fixes a second latent divergence the old code had: csv.reader's non-strict handling of '"a"b,c' (yields 'ab'), which the break-on-closing-quote logic got wrong. Then: (a) extend the Rust unit test core_classes_csv_first_field_matches_python_csv_reader with the multiline case ("\"Weird\nClass\"\n" → {"Weird\nClass"}) and the '"a"b' case, validating expected values against Python csv.reader; (b) add a Python↔Rust parity case in tests/test_clankerprof_rust_parity.py using a --core-classes file with an embedded-newline quoted class and a matching leaf; (c) no spec change needed — the spec already states the correct contract — but optionally add "including quoted fields spanning newlines" to docs/CLANKERPROF_SPEC.md:329-332 to pin the case explicitly.

